  "prompt": "Can an L2 visa holder work without EAD?",
  "response": "An L2 visa is issued to the dependent spouse and children (unmarried and under 21) of an L1 visa holders who are in the United States as intracompany transferees. The rules regarding work authorization for L2 visa holders vary depending on the specific category within the L2 visa.\n\n1. **L2 Spouse**: As of the current regulations, **L2 spouses** are eligible to work in the United States **without needing to obtain an Employment Authorization Document (EAD)**. This was established by the **spousal work authorization rule**, which allows L2 spouses to work legally in the U.S. as long as they have an approved L2 visa and their L1 spouse is maintaining valid L1 status. However, starting at the end of 2021, U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) began requiring L2 spouses to receive an EAD to work legally. As of now, it is advisable for L2 spouses to apply for and obtain an EAD before starting employment.\n\n2. **L2 Children**: L2 children are not permitted to work in the United States. Their visa status does not provide any work authorization, and they must maintain their status as dependents.\n\nIt is important to stay updated on U.S. immigration policies, as rules and regulations can change. If you or someone you know is an L2 visa holder, it is recommended to consult with an immigration attorney or check the latest guidance from USCIS to ensure compliance with current laws.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
